ASMJIT_API Error _grow(size_t n)

Grow the internal buffer.

The internal buffer will grow at least by n bytes so n bytes can be added to it. If n is zero or getOffset() + n is not greater than the current capacity of the buffer this function won’t do anything.

ASMJIT_API Error _reserve(size_t n)

Reserve the internal buffer to at least n bytes.

size_t relocCode(void * dst)

Simplifed version of relocCode() method designed for JIT.

This is an overloaded member function, provided for convenience. It differs from the above function only in what argument(s) it accepts.

size_t relocCode(void * dst, Ptr base)

Relocate code to a given address dst.

A given buffer will be overwritten, to get number of bytes required use getCodeSize().

Parameters
  • dst -

    Where the relocated code should me stored. The pointer can be address returned by virtual memory allocator or your own address if you want only to store the code for later reuse (or load, etc...).

  • addressBase -

    Base address used for relocation. When using JIT code generation, this will be the same as dst, only casted to system integer type. But when generating code for remote process then the value can be different.

Return Value
  • The -

    bytes used. Code-generator can create trampolines which are used when calling other functions inside the JIT code. However, these trampolines can be unused so the relocCode() returns the exact size needed for the function.

size_t _relocCode(void * dst, Ptr base)

Reloc code (virtual).

ASMJIT_API void * make()

Make is a convenience method to make and relocate the current code into the associated runtime.

What is needed is only to cast the returned pointer to your function type and then use it. If there was an error during make() NULL is returned and the last error code can be obtained by calling getError().

Error fetch()

Fetch.

Fetch iterates over all nodes and gathers information about all variables used. The process generates information required by register allocator, variable liveness analysis and translator.

Error removeUnreachableCode()

Remove unreachable code.

Error analyze()

Preform variable liveness analysis.

Analysis phase iterates over nodes in reverse order and generates a bit array describing variables that are alive at every node in the function. When the analysis start all variables are assumed dead. When a read or read/write operations of a variable is detected the variable becomes alive; when only write operation is detected the variable becomes dead.

When a label is found all jumps to that label are followed and analysis repeats until all variables are resolved.

Error annotate()

Error translate()

Translate code by allocating registers and handling state changes.

void cleanup()

Error compile(FuncNode * func)

Error serialize(BaseAssembler * assembler, BaseNode * start, BaseNode * stop)

struct asmjit::BaseLogger
#include <logger.h>

Abstract logging class.

This class can be inherited and reimplemented to fit into your logging subsystem. When reimplementing use asmjit::Logger::log() method to log into your stream.

This class also contain _enabled member that can be used to enable or disable logging.

Public Functions

ASMJIT_API BaseLogger()

Create a BaseLogger instance.

ASMJIT_API ~BaseLogger()

Destroy the BaseLogger instance.

void logString(uint32_t style, const char * buf, size_t len = kInvalidIndex)

Abstract method to log output.

Default implementation that is in asmjit::Logger is to do nothing. It’s virtual to fit to your logging system.

ASMJIT_API void logFormat(uint32_t style, const char * fmt, ...)

Log formatter message (like sprintf) sending output to logString() method.

ASMJIT_API void logBinary(uint32_t style, const void * data, size_t size)

Log binary data.

Error add(void ** dst, BaseAssembler * assembler)

Allocate memory for code generated in assembler and reloc it to the target location.

This method is universal allowing any preprocessing / postprocessing with code generated by BaseAssembler or BaseCompiler. Because BaseCompiler always uses BaseAssembler it’s allowed to access only the BaseAssembler instance.

This method is always last step when using code generation. You can use it to allocate memory for JIT code, saving code to remote process or a file.

struct asmjit::ErrorHandler

Public Functions

ASMJIT_API ErrorHandler()

Create a new ErrorHandler.

ASMJIT_API ~ErrorHandler()

Destroy the ErrorHandler.

ASMJIT_API ErrorHandler * addRef()

Reference this error handler.

Note
This member function is provided for convenience. The default implementation does nothing. If you are working in environment where multiple ErrorHandler instances are used in different Assembler and Compiler instances (or in multithreaded environment) you might want to provide your own functionality for reference counting. In that case override addRef() and release() functions to inc/dec your reference count value.

ASMJIT_API void release()

Release this error handler.

Note
This member function is provided for convenience. See addRef() for more detailed information related to reference counting.

bool handleError(Error code, const char * message)

Error handler (pure).

Error handler is called when an error happened. An error can happen in many places, but error handler is mostly used by Assembler and Compiler classes to report anything that may prevent correct code generation. There are multiple ways how the error handler can be used and each has it’s pros/cons.

AsmJit library doesn’t use exceptions and can be compiled with or without exception feature support. Even if the AsmJit library is compiled without exceptions it is exception-safe and handleError() can report an incoming error by throwing an exception of any type. It’s guaranteed that the exception won’t be catched by AsmJit and will be propagated to the code calling AsmJit Assembler or Compiler. Alternative to throwing exception is using setjmp() / longjmp() pair from the standard C library.

If the exception or setjmp() / longjmp() mechanism is used, the state of the Assember or Compiler is unchanged and if it’s possible the execution (instruction serialization) can continue. However if the error happened during any phase that translates or modifies the stored code (for example relocation done by Assembler or analysis/translation done by Compiler) the execution can’t continue and the error will be also stored in Assembler or Compiler.

Finally, if exceptions nor setjmp() / longjmp() mechanisms were used, you can still implement a compatible design by returning from your error handler. Returning true means that error was reported and AsmJit should continue execution. When false is returned, AsmJit sets the error immediately to the Assembler or Compiler and execution shouldn’t continue (this is the default behavior in case no error handler is used).

struct asmjit::FuncNode
#include <compiler.h>

Function declaration node.

Functions are base blocks for generating assembler output. Each generated assembler stream needs standard entry and leave sequences which are compatible with the operating system ABI.

FuncNode can be used to generate function prolog and epilog which are compatible with a given function calling convention and to allocate and manage variables that can be allocated/spilled during compilation phase.

struct asmjit::Label
#include <defs.h>

Label (jump target or data location).

Label represents locations typically used as jump targets, but may be also used as position where are stored constants or static variables. If you want to use Label you need first to associate it with BaseAssembler or BaseCompiler instance. To create new label use BaseAssembler::newLabel() or BaseCompiler::newLabel().

Example of using labels:

 // Create Assembler/Compiler.
 Assembler a;

 // Create Label instance.
 Label L_1(a);

 // ... your code ...

 // Using label, see @ref asmjit::BaseAssembler or @ref asmjit::BaseCompiler.
 a.jump(L_1);

 // ... your code ...

 // Bind label to current position, see @ref asmjit::BaseAssembler::bind()
 // or @ref asmjit::BaseCompiler::bind().
 a.bind(L_1);

Public Functions

Label()

Create new, unassociated label.

Label(uint32_t id)

Label(BaseAssembler & a)

Create new initialized label.

Label(BaseCompiler & c)

Create new initialized label.

Label(const Label & other)

Create reference to another label.

Label(const _NoInit &)

Label & operator=(const Label & other)

bool operator==(const Label & other)

bool operator!=(const Label & other)

struct asmjit::MemoryManager
#include <memorymanager.h>

Virtual memory manager interface.

This class is pure virtual. You can get default virtual memory manager using getGlobal() method. If you want to create more memory managers with same functionality as global memory manager use VirtualMemoryManager class.

Public Functions

ASMJIT_API MemoryManager()

Create memory manager instance.

ASMJIT_API ~MemoryManager()

Destroy memory manager instance, this means also to free all memory blocks.

void reset()

Free all allocated memory.

void * alloc(size_t size, uint32_t type = kVirtualAllocFreeable)

Allocate a size bytes of virtual memory.

Note that if you are implementing your own virtual memory manager then you can quitly ignore type of allocation. This is mainly for AsmJit to memory manager that allocated memory will be never freed.

Error release(void * address)

Free previously allocated memory at a given address.

Error shrink(void * address, size_t used)

Free some tail memory.

size_t getUsedBytes()

Get how many bytes are currently used.

size_t getAllocatedBytes()

Get how many bytes are currently allocated.

Public Static Functions

ASMJIT_API MemoryManager * getGlobal()

Get global memory manager instance.

Global instance is instance of VirtualMemoryManager class. Global memory manager is used by default by Assembler::make() and Compiler::make() methods.

struct asmjit::RelocData
#include <assembler.h>

Code relocation data (relative vs absolute addresses).

X86/X64:

X86 architecture uses 32-bit absolute addressing model by memory operands, but 64-bit mode uses relative addressing model (RIP + displacement). In code we are always using relative addressing model for referencing labels and embedded data. In 32-bit mode we must patch all references to absolute address before we can call generated function.

Public Members

uint32_t type

Type of relocation.

uint32_t size

Size of relocation (4 or 8 bytes).

Ptr from

Offset from code begin address.

Ptr data

Relative displacement from code begin address (not to offset) or absolute address.

struct asmjit::StringBuilder

String builder was designed to be able to build a string using append like operation to append numbers, other strings, or signle characters. It can allocate it’s own buffer or use a buffer created on the stack.

VarData * _vd

uint32_t _flags

Flags.

uint8_t _varCount

How many times the variable is used by the instruction/node.

uint8_t _inRegIndex

Input register index or kInvalidReg if it’s not given.

Even if the input register index is not given (i.e. it may by any register), register allocator should assign an index that will be used to persist a variable into this specific index. It’s helpful in situations where one variable has to be allocated in multiple registers to determine the register which will be persistent.

uint8_t _outRegIndex

Output register index or kInvalidReg if it’s not given.

Typically kInvalidReg if variable is only used on input.

uint8_t _reserved

uint32_t _packed

union asmjit::VarAttr::@4 @5

uint32_t _inRegs

Mandatory input registers.

Mandatory input registers are required by the instruction even if there are duplicates. This schema allows us to allocate one variable in one or more register when needed. Required mostly by instructions that have implicit register operands (imul, cpuid, ...) and function call.

uint32_t _allocableRegs

Allocable input registers.

Optional input registers is a mask of all allocable registers for a given variable where we have to pick one of them. This mask is usually not used when _inRegs is set. If both masks are used then the register allocator tries first to find an intersection between these and allocates an extra slot if not found.

uint8_t _isCalculated

Whether variable content can be calculated by a simple instruction.

This is used mainly by MMX and SSE2 code. This flag indicates that register allocator should never reserve memory for this variable, because the content can be generated by a single instruction (for example PXOR).

uint32_t mWriteCount

Memory write statistics.

VarAttr * _va

Temporary link to VarAttr* used by the Context used in various phases, but always set back to NULL when finished.

This temporary data is designed to be used by algorithms that need to store some data into variables themselves during compilation. But it’s expected that after variable is compiled & translated the data is set back to zero/null. Initial value is NULL.

struct asmjit::VirtualMemoryManager
#include <memorymanager.h>

Reference implementation of memory manager that uses asmjit::VMem class to allocate chunks of virtual memory and bit arrays to manage it.

Public Functions

ASMJIT_API VirtualMemoryManager()

Create a VirtualMemoryManager instance.

ASMJIT_API ~VirtualMemoryManager()

Destroy the VirtualMemoryManager instance, this means also to free all blocks.

ASMJIT_API void reset()

Free all allocated memory.

ASMJIT_API void * alloc(size_t size, uint32_t type = kVirtualAllocFreeable)

Allocate a size bytes of virtual memory.

Note that if you are implementing your own virtual memory manager then you can quitly ignore type of allocation. This is mainly for AsmJit to memory manager that allocated memory will be never freed.

ASMJIT_API Error release(void * address)

Free previously allocated memory at a given address.

ASMJIT_API Error shrink(void * address, size_t used)

Free some tail memory.

ASMJIT_API size_t getUsedBytes()

Get how many bytes are currently used.

ASMJIT_API size_t getAllocatedBytes()

Get how many bytes are currently allocated.

ASMJIT_API bool getKeepVirtualMemory()

Get whether to keep allocated memory after memory manager is destroyed.

See
setKeepVirtualMemory().

ASMJIT_API void setKeepVirtualMemory(bool keepVirtualMemory)

Set whether to keep allocated memory after memory manager is destroyed.

This method is usable when patching code of remote process. You need to allocate process memory, store generated assembler into it and patch the method you want to redirect (into your code). This method affects only VirtualMemoryManager destructor. After destruction all internal structures are freed, only the process virtual memory remains.

Note
Memory allocated with kVirtualAllocPermanent is always kept.
See
getKeepVirtualMemory().

Public Members

void * _d

Pointer to private data hidden out of the public API.

struct asmjit::VMem
#include <vmem.h>

Class that helps with allocating memory for executing code generated by JIT compiler.

There are defined functions that provides facility to allocate and free memory where can be executed code. If processor and operating system supports execution protection then you can’t run code from normally malloc()’ed memory.

Functions are internally implemented by operating system dependent way. VirtualAlloc() function is used for Windows operating system and mmap() for posix ones. If you want to study or create your own functions, look at VirtualAlloc() or mmap() documentation (depends on you target OS).

Under posix operating systems is also useable mprotect() function, that can enable execution protection to malloc()’ed memory block.

Public Static Functions

ASMJIT_API void * alloc(size_t length, size_t * allocated, bool canExecute)

Allocate virtual memory.

Pages are readable/writeable, but they are not guaranteed to be executable unless ‘canExecute’ is true. Returns the address of allocated memory, or NULL on failure.

ASMJIT_API void release(void * addr, size_t length)

Free memory allocated by alloc()

ASMJIT_API size_t getAlignment()

Get the alignment guaranteed by alloc().

ASMJIT_API size_t getPageSize()

Get size of the single page.

struct asmjit::x86x64::InstInfo
#include <x86defs.h>

X86 instruction information.

Public Functions

const char * getName()

Get instruction name string (null terminated string).

uint32_t _getNameIndex()

Get instruction name index (index to _instName array).

uint32_t getGroup()

Get instruction group, see kInstGroup.

uint32_t getFlags()

Get instruction flags, see kInstFlags.

bool isFlow()

Get whether the instruction is a control-flow intruction.

Control flow instruction is instruction that modifies instruction pointer, typically jmp, jcc, call, or ret.

bool isTest()

Get whether the instruction is a compare/test like intruction.

bool isMove()

Get whether the instruction is a typical Move instruction.

Move instructions typically overwrite the first operand, so it’s an useful hint for Compiler. Applies also to multimedia instruction - MMX, SSE, SSE2 and AVX moves).

bool isXchg()

Get whether the instruction is a typical Exchange instruction.

Exchange instructios are ‘xchg’ and ‘xadd’.

bool isFp()

Get whether the instruction accesses Fp register(s).

bool isLockable()

Get whether the instruction can be prefixed by LOCK prefix.

bool isSpecial()

Get whether the instruction is special type (this is used by Compiler to manage additional variables or functionality).

bool isSpecialMem()

Get whether the instruction is special type and it performs memory access.

Public Members

uint16_t _nameIndex

Instruction name index in _instName[] array.

uint16_t _flags

Instruction flags.

uint8_t _group

Instruction group, used also by Compiler.

uint8_t _reserved[3]

Reserved for future use.

uint16_t _opFlags[4]

Operands’ flags.

uint32_t _opCode[2]

Primary and secondary opcodes.

Find VarAttr.

VarAttr * findVaByClass(uint32_t c, VarData * vd)

Find VarAttr (by class).

Public Members

uint32_t _vaCount

Variables count.

RegMask _inRegs

Special registers on input.

Special register(s) restricted to one or more physical register. If there is more than one special register it means that we have to duplicate the variable content to all of them (it means that the same varible was used by two or more operands). We forget about duplicates after the register allocation finishes and marks all duplicates as non-assigned.

RegMask _outRegs

Special registers on output.

Special register(s) used on output. Each variable can have only one special register on the output, ‘VarInst’ contains all registers from all ‘VarAttr’s.

RegMask _clobberedRegs

Clobbered registers (by a function call).

RegCount _start

Start indexes of variables per register class.

RegCount _count

Count of variables per register class.

VarAttr _list[1]

VarAttr list.

#include <x86compiler.h>

  • kGpIndex = 0 -

  • kMmIndex = kGpIndex + kGpCount -

    Base index for Mm registers.

  • kMmCount = 8 -

    Count of Mm registers.

  • kXmmIndex = kMmIndex + kMmCount -

  • kXmmCount = 16 -

    Count of Xmm registers.

struct asmjit::x86x64::X86X64Assembler
#include <x86assembler.h>

X86/X64 assembler.

Assembler is the main class in AsmJit that can encode instructions and their operands to a binary stream runnable by CPU. It creates internal buffer where the encodes instructions are stored and it contains intrinsics that can be used to emit the code in a convenent way. Code generation is in general safe, because the intrinsics uses method overloading so even the code is emitted it can be checked by a C++ compiler. It’s nearly impossible to create invalid instruction (for example mov [eax], [eax], because such overload doesn’t exist.

Each call to an assembler intrinsic function emits instruction directly to the binary stream. There are also runtime checks that prevent invalid code to be emitted. It will assert in debug mode and put the Assembler instance to an error state in production mode.

Public Functions

ASMJIT_API X86X64Assembler(BaseRuntime * runtime)

Public Members

X86 declaration.

RegMask _usedArgs

Mask of all registers actually used to pass function arguments.

Note
This bit-mask is not the same as X86X64Func::_passed. It contains only registers actually used to do the call while X86X64Func::_passed mask contains all registers for all function prototype combinations.

struct asmjit::x86x64::X86X64Compiler
#include <x86compiler.h>

X86/X64 compiler.

This class is used to store instruction stream and allows to modify it on the fly. It uses different concept than asmjit::Assembler class and in fact asmjit::Assembler is only used as a backend. Compiler never emits machine code and each instruction you use is stored to instruction array instead. This allows to modify instruction stream later and for example to reorder instructions to make better performance.

asmjit::X86X64Compiler moves code generation to a higher level. Higher level constructs allows to write more abstract and extensible code that is not possible with pure asmjit::Assembler class. Because asmjit::Compiler needs to create many objects and lifetime of these objects is small (same as asmjit::Compiler lifetime itself) it uses very fast memory management model. This model allows to create object instances in nearly zero time (compared to malloc() or new() operators) so overhead by creating machine code by asmjit::Compiler is minimized.

ASMJIT_API X86X64FuncNode * newFunc(uint32_t conv, const FuncPrototype & p)

Create a new X86X64FuncNode.

ASMJIT_API X86X64FuncNode * addFunc(uint32_t conv, const FuncPrototype & p)

Add a new function.

This method is usually used as a first step when generating functions by Compiler. First parameter cconv specifies function calling convention to use. Second parameter params specifies function arguments. To create function arguments are used templates BuildFunction0<...>, BuildFunction1<...>, BuildFunction2<...>, etc...

Parameters
  • cconv -

    Calling convention to use (see kFuncConv enum)

  • params -

    Function arguments prototype.

Templates with BuildFunction prefix are used to generate argument IDs based on real C++ types. See next example how to generate function with two 32-bit integer arguments.

 // Building function using asmjit::Compiler example.

 // Compiler instance
 Compiler c;

 // Begin of function (also emits function @c Prolog)
 c.addFunc(
   // Default calling convention (32-bit cdecl or 64-bit for host OS)
   kFuncConvHost,
   // Using function builder to generate arguments list
   BuildFunction2<FnVoid, int, int>());

 // End of function (also emits function @c Epilog)
 c.endFunc();

You can see that building functions is really easy. Previous code snipped will generate code for function with two 32-bit integer arguments. You can access arguments by asmjit::Function::argument() method. Arguments are indexed from 0 (like everything in C).

 // Accessing function arguments through asmjit::Function example.

 // Compiler instance
 Compiler c;
 GpVar a0(c, kVarTypeInt32);
 GpVar a1(c, kVarTypeInt32);

 // Begin of function (also emits function @c Prolog)
 c.addFunc(
   // Default calling convention (32-bit cdecl or 64-bit for host OS)
   kFuncConvHost,
   // Using function builder to generate arguments list
   BuildFunction2<FnVoid, int, int>());

 c.setArg(0, a0);
 c.setArg(1, a1);

 // Use them.
 c.add(a0, a1);

 // End of function - emits function epilog and return instruction.
 c.endFunc();

Arguments are like variables. How to manipulate with variables is documented in asmjit::Compiler, variables section.

Note
To get current function use currentFunction() method or save pointer to asmjit::Function returned by asmjit::Compiler::addFunc<> method. Recommended is to save the pointer.
See
BuildFunction0, BuildFunction1, BuildFunction2, ...

ASMJIT_API EndNode * endFunc()

End of current function.

X86X64FuncNode * getFunc()

Get current function as X86X64FuncNode.

This method can be called within addFunc() and endFunc() block to get current function you are working with. It’s recommended to store asmjit::Function pointer returned by addFunc<> method, because this allows you in future implement function sections outside of function itself (yeah, this is possible!).

ASMJIT_API void getMemoryHome(BaseVar & var, GpVar * home, int * displacement = NULL)

Get memory home of variable var.

ASMJIT_API void setMemoryHome(BaseVar & var, const GpVar & home, int displacement = 0)

Set memory home of variable var.

Default memory home location is on stack (ESP/RSP), but when needed the bebahior can be changed by this method.

It is an error to chaining memory home locations. For example the given code is invalid:

 Compiler c;

 ...

 GpVar v0(c, kVarTypeIntPtr);
 GpVar v1(c, kVarTypeIntPtr);
 GpVar v2(c, kVarTypeIntPtr);
 GpVar v3(c, kVarTypeIntPtr);

 c.setMemoryHome(v1, v0, 0); // Allowed, [v0+0] is memory home for v1.
 c.setMemoryHome(v2, v0, 4); // Allowed, [v0+4] is memory home for v2.
 c.setMemoryHome(v3, v2);    // CHAINING, NOT ALLOWED!

ASMJIT_API Error _newStack(BaseMem * mem, uint32_t size, uint32_t alignment, const char * name)

template < int C >
void attach(VarData * vd, uint32_t regIndex, bool modified)

Attach.

Attach a register to the ‘VarData‘, changing ‘VarData‘ members to show that the variable is currently alive and linking variable with the current ‘VarState‘.

template < int C >
void detach(VarData * vd, uint32_t regIndex, uint32_t vState)

Detach.

The opposite of ‘Attach’. Detach resets the members in ‘VarData‘ (regIndex, state and changed flags) and unlinks the variable with the current ‘VarState‘.

template < int C >
void rebase(VarData * vd, uint32_t newRegIndex, uint32_t oldRegIndex)

Rebase.

Change the register of the ‘VarData‘ changing also the current ‘VarState‘. Rebase is nearly identical to ‘Detach’ and ‘Attach’ sequence, but doesn’t

template < int C >
void load(VarData * vd, uint32_t regIndex)

Load.

Load variable from its memory slot to a register, emitting ‘Load’ instruction and changing the variable state to allocated.

template < int C >
void save(VarData * vd)

Save.

Save the variable into its home location, but keep it as allocated.

template < int C >
void move(VarData * vd, uint32_t regIndex)

Move a register.

Move register from one index to another, emitting ‘Move’ if needed. This function does nothing if register is already at the given index.

void swapGp(VarData * aVd, VarData * bVd)

Swap two registers.

It’s only possible to swap Gp registers.

template < int C >
void alloc(VarData * vd, uint32_t regIndex)

Alloc.

template < int C >
void spill(VarData * vd)

Spill.

Spill variable/register, saves the content to the memory-home if modified.

template < int C >
void modify(VarData * vd)

template < int C >
void unuse(VarData * vd, uint32_t vState = kVarStateUnused)

Unuse.

Unuse variable, it will be detached it if it’s allocated then its state will be changed to kVarStateUnused.

struct asmjit::Zone
#include <zone.h>

Fast incremental memory allocator.

Memory allocator designed to allocate small objects that will be invalidated (free) all at once.

Public Functions

ASMJIT_API Zone(size_t chunkSize)

Create a new instance of Zone allocator.

Parameters
  • chunkSize -

    Default size of the first chunk.

ASMJIT_API ~Zone()

Destroy Zone instance.

ASMJIT_API void clear()

Free all allocated memory except first block that remains for reuse.

Note that this method will invalidate all instances using this memory allocated by this zone instance.

ASMJIT_API void reset()

Free all allocated memory at once.

Note that this method will invalidate all instances using this memory allocated by this zone instance.

size_t getChunkSize()

Get (default) chunk size.

void * alloc(size_t size)

Allocate size bytes of memory.

Pointer allocated by this way will be valid until Zone object is destroyed. To create class by this way use placement new and delete operators:

 // Example of simple class allocation.
 using namespace asmjit

 // Your class.
 class Object
 {
   // members...
 };

 // Your function
 void f()
 {
   // Create zone object with chunk size of 65536 bytes.
   Zone zone(65536);

   // Create your objects using zone object allocating, for example:
   Object* obj = new(zone.alloc(sizeof(YourClass))) Object();

   // ... lifetime of your objects ...

   // Destroy your objects:
   obj->~Object();

   // Zone destructor will free all memory allocated through it, you can
   // call @c zone.reset() if you wan't to reuse current @ref Zone.
 }

template < typename T >
T * allocT(size_t size = sizeof(T))

Like alloc(), but returns T*.

ASMJIT_API void * _alloc(size_t size)

void * calloc(size_t size)

Allocate size bytes of zeroed memory.

ASMJIT_API void * _calloc(size_t size)

ASMJIT_API void * dup(const void * data, size_t size)

Helper to duplicate data.

ASMJIT_API char * sdup(const char * str)

Helper to duplicate string.

ASMJIT_API char * sformat(const char * str, ...)

Helper to duplicate formatted string, maximum length is 256 bytes.

Public Members

typedef uint32_t Error

Enums

kCodeGen enum

CodeGen features.

Values:

  • kCodeGenOptimizedAlign = 0 -

    Emit optimized code-alignment sequences.

    X86/X64:

    Default align sequence used by X86/X64 architecture is one-byte 0x90 opcode that is mostly shown by disassemblers as nop. However there are more optimized align sequences for 2-11 bytes that may execute faster. If this feature is enabled asmjit will generate specialized sequences for alignment between 1 to 11 bytes. Also when x86x64::Compiler is used, it may add rex prefixes into the code to make some instructions larger so no alignment sequences are needed.

    true.

  • kCodeGenPredictedJumps = 1 -

    Emit jump-prediction hints.

    X86/X64:

    Jump prediction is usually based on the direction of the jump. If the jump is backward it is usually predicted as taken; and if the jump is forward it is usually predicted as not-taken. The reason is that loops generally use backward jumps and conditions usually use forward jumps. However this behavior can be overridden by using instruction prefixes. If this option is enabled these hints will be emitted.

    true.

Anonymous enum

Values:

  • kBaseCompilerDefaultLookAhead = 64 -

kVarAttrFlags enum

Variable attribute flags.

Values:

  • kVarAttrInReg = 0x00000001 -

    Variable is accessed through register on input.

  • kVarAttrOutReg = 0x00000002 -

    Variable is accessed through register on output.

  • kVarAttrInOutReg = 0x00000003 -

    Variable is accessed through register on input & output.

  • kVarAttrInMem = 0x00000004 -

    Variable is accessed through memory on input.

  • kVarAttrOutMem = 0x00000008 -

    Variable is accessed through memory on output.

  • kVarAttrInOutMem = 0x0000000C -

    Variable is accessed through memory on input & output.

  • kVarAttrInDecide = 0x00000010 -

    It can be decided whether it’s better to alloc variable to register or memory on the input.

  • kVarAttrOutDecide = 0x00000020 -

    It can be decided whether it’s better to alloc variable to register or memory on the output.

  • kVarAttrInOutDecide = 0x00000030 -

    It can be decided whether it’s better to alloc variable to register or memory on the input & output.

  • kVarAttrInConv = 0x00000040 -

    Variable is converted to other type/class on the input.

  • kVarAttrOutConv = 0x00000080 -

    Variable is converted from other type/class on the output.

  • kVarAttrInOutConv = 0x000000C0 -

    Combination of kVarAttrInConv and kVarAttrOutConv.

  • kVarAttrInCall = 0x00000100 -

    Variable is a function call operand.

  • kVarAttrInArg = 0x00000200 -

    Variable is a function argument passed in register.

  • kVarAttrOutRet = 0x00000400 -

    Variable is a function return value passed in register.

  • kVarAttrUnuse = 0x00000800 -

    Variable should be unused at the end of the instruction/node.

  • kVarAttrInAll = kVarAttrInReg | kVarAttrInMem | kVarAttrInDecide | kVarAttrInCall | kVarAttrInArg -
  • kVarAttrOutAll = kVarAttrOutReg | kVarAttrOutMem | kVarAttrOutDecide | kVarAttrOutRet -
  • kVarAttrAllocInDone = 0x00400000 -

    Variable is already allocated on the input.

  • kVarAttrAllocOutDone = 0x00800000 -

    Variable is already allocated on the output.

kVarHint enum

Variable hint (used by BaseCompiler).

See
BaseCompiler.

Values:

  • kVarHintAlloc = 0 -

    Alloc variable.

  • kVarHintSpill = 1 -

    Spill variable.

  • kVarHintSave = 2 -

    Save variable if modified.

  • kVarHintSaveAndUnuse = 3 -

    Save variable if modified and mark it as unused.

  • kVarHintUnuse = 4 -

    Mark variable as unused.

kVarState enum

State of variable.

Note
State of variable is used only during make process and it’s not visible to the developer.

Values:

  • kVarStateUnused = 0 -

    Variable is currently not used.

  • kVarStateReg = 1 -

    Variable is in register.

    Variable is currently allocated in register.

  • kVarStateMem = 2 -

    Variable is in memory location or spilled.

    Variable was spilled from register to memory or variable is used for memory only storage.

kInstCode enum

Instruction codes (stub).

Values:

  • kInstNone = 0 -

    No instruction.

kInstOptions enum

Instruction options (stub).

Values:

  • kInstOptionNone = 0x00 -

    No instruction options.

  • kInstOptionShortForm = 0x01 -

    Emit short form of the instruction.

    X86/X64:

    Short form is mostly related to jmp and jcc instructions, but can be used by other instructions supporting 8-bit or 32-bit immediates. This option can be dangerous if the short jmp/jcc is required, but not encodable due to large displacement, in such case an error happens and the whole assembler/compiler stream is unusable.

  • kInstOptionLongForm = 0x02 -

    Emit long form of the instruction.

    X86/X64:

    Long form is mosrlt related to jmp and jcc instructions, but like the kInstOptionShortForm option it can be used by other instructions supporting both 8-bit and 32-bit immediates.

  • kInstOptionTaken = 0x04 -

    Condition is likely to be taken (instruction).

  • kInstOptionNotTaken = 0x08 -

    Condition is unlikely to be taken (instruction).

kMemType enum

Type of memory operand.

Values:

  • kMemTypeBaseIndex = 0 -

    Memory operand is a combination of base register, optional index register and optional displacement.

    Note

    The Assembler interprets kMemTypeBaseIndex and kMemTypeStackIndex types the same way, but Compiler interprets kMemTypeBaseIndex as [base + index] and kMemTypeStackIndex as [stack(base) + index].

  • kMemTypeStackIndex = 1 -

    Memory operand is a combination of variable’s memory location, optional index register and displacement.

    Note

    The Assembler interprets kMemTypeBaseIndex and kMemTypeStackIndex types in the same way, but Compiler interprets kMemTypeBaseIndex as [base + index] and kMemTypeStackIndex as [stack(base) + index].

  • kMemTypeLabel = 2 -

    Memory operand refers to the memory location specified by a label.

  • kMemTypeAbsolute = 3 -

    Memory operand is an absolute memory location.

    Supported mostly by x86, truncated to a 32-bit value when running in 64-bit mode (x64).

kVarType enum

Values:

  • kVarTypeInt8 = 0 -

    Variable is signed 8-bit integer.

  • kVarTypeUInt8 = 1 -

    Variable is unsigned 8-bit integer.

  • kVarTypeInt16 = 2 -

    Variable is signed 16-bit integer.

  • kVarTypeUInt16 = 3 -

    Variable is unsigned 16-bit integer.

  • kVarTypeInt32 = 4 -

    Variable is signed 32-bit integer.

  • kVarTypeUInt32 = 5 -

    Variable is unsigned 32-bit integer.

  • kVarTypeInt64 = 6 -

    Variable is signed 64-bit integer.

  • kVarTypeUInt64 = 7 -

    Variable is unsigned 64-bit integer.

  • kVarTypeIntPtr = 8 -

    Variable is target intptr_t (not compatible with host intptr_t).

  • kVarTypeUIntPtr = 9 -

    Variable is target uintptr_t (not compatible with host uintptr_t).

  • kVarTypeFp32 = 10 -

    Variable is 32-bit floating point (single precision).

  • kVarTypeFp64 = 11 -

    Variable is 64-bit floating point (double precision).

  • kVarTypeInvalid = 0xFF -

    Invalid variable type.

  • _kVarTypeIntStart = kVarTypeInt8 -
  • _kVarTypeIntEnd = kVarTypeUIntPtr -
  • _kVarTypeFpStart = kVarTypeFp32 -
  • _kVarTypeFpEnd = kVarTypeFp64 -

kError enum

AsmJit error codes.

Values:

  • kErrorOk = 0 -

    No error (success).

    This is default state and state you want.

  • kErrorNoHeapMemory = 1 -

    Heap memory allocation failed.

  • kErrorNoVirtualMemory = 2 -

    Virtual memory allocation failed.

  • kErrorInvalidArgument = 3 -

    Invalid argument.

  • kErrorInvalidState = 4 -

    Invalid state.

  • kErrorAssemblerUnknownInst = 5 -

    Unknown instruction. This happens only if instruction code is out of bounds. Shouldn’t happen.

  • kErrorAssemblerIllegalInst = 6 -

    Illegal instruction, usually generated by asmjit::Assembler class when emitting instruction opcode. If this error is generated the target buffer is not affected by this invalid instruction.

    You can also get this status code if you are under x64 (64-bit x86) and you tried to decode instruction using AH, BH, CH or DH register with REX prefix. These registers can’t be accessed if REX prefix is used and AsmJit didn’t check for this situation in intrinsics (Compiler takes care of this and rearrange registers if needed).

    Examples that will raise kErrorAssemblerIllegalInst error (a is Assembler instance):

     a.mov(dword_ptr(eax), al); // Invalid address size.
 a.mov(byte_ptr(r10), ah);  // Undecodable instruction (AH used with r10
                            // that can be encoded by using REX prefix only)

    Note

    In debug mode you get assertion failure instead of setting error code.

  • kErrorAssemblerIllegalAddr = 7 -

    Illegal addressing used (unencodable).

  • kErrorAssemblerIllegalShortJump = 8 -

    Short jump instruction used, but displacement is out of bounds.

  • kErrorCompilerNoFunc = 9 -

    No function defined.

  • kErrorCompilerIncompleteFunc = 10 -

    Function generation is not finished by using Compiler::endFunc() or something bad happened during generation related to function. This can be missing compiler node, etc...

  • kErrorCompilerOverlappedArgs = 11 -

    Tried to generate a function with overlapped arguments.

  • kErrorCompilerNoRegs = 12 -

    Compiler can’t allocate registers.

  • kErrorCompilerOverlappedRegs = 13 -

    Compiler can’t allocate registers, because they overlap.

  • kErrorCompilerIncompatibleArg = 14 -

    Tried to call function with an incompatible argument.

  • kErrorCompilerIncompatibleRet = 15 -

    Incompatible return value.

  • kErrorCount = 16 -

    Count of AsmJit status codes. Can grow in future.

kFuncConv enum

Values:

  • kFuncConvNone = 0 -

    Calling convention is invalid (can’t be used).

kFuncHint enum

Function hints.

Values:

  • kFuncHintNaked = 0 -

    Make a naked function (default true).

    Naked function is function without using standard prolog/epilog sequence).

  • kFuncHintCompact = 1 -

    Generate compact function prolog/epilog if possible.

kFuncFlags enum

Function flags.

Values:

  • kFuncFlagIsNaked = 0x00000001 -

    Whether the function is using naked (minimal) prolog / epilog.

  • kFuncFlagIsCaller = 0x00000002 -

    Whether an another function is called from this function.

  • kFuncFlagIsStackMisaligned = 0x00000004 -

    Whether the stack is not aligned to the required stack alignment, thus it has to be aligned manually.

  • kFuncFlagIsStackAdjusted = 0x00000008 -

    Whether the stack pointer is adjusted by the stack size needed to save registers and function variables.

  • kFuncFlagIsFinished = 0x80000000 -

    Whether the function is finished using Compiler::endFunc().

kFuncDir enum

Function arguments direction.

Values:

  • kFuncDirLtr = 0 -

    Arguments are passed left to right.

    This arguments direction is unusual to C programming, it’s used by pascal compilers and in some calling conventions by Borland compiler).

  • kFuncDirRtl = 1 -

    Arguments are passed right ro left.

    This is default argument direction in C programming.

Anonymous enum

Values:

  • kFuncStackInvalid = -1 -

    Invalid stack offset in function or function parameter.

kFuncArg enum

Function argument (lo/hi) specification.

Values:

  • kFuncArgCount = 16 -

    Maxumum number of function arguments supported by AsmJit.

  • kFuncArgCountLoHi = kFuncArgCount * 2 -

    Extended maximum number of arguments (used internally).

  • kFuncArgLo = 0 -

    Index to the LO part of function argument (default).

    This value is typically omitted and added only if there is HI argument accessed.

  • kFuncArgHi = kFuncArgCount -

    Index to the HI part of function argument.

    HI part of function argument depends on target architecture. On x86 it’s typically used to transfer 64-bit integers (they form a pair of 32-bit integers).

kFuncRet enum

Function return value (lo/hi) specification.

Values:

  • kFuncRetLo = 0 -

    Index to the LO part of function return value.

  • kFuncRetHi = 1 -

    Index to the HI part of function return value.

kGlobals enum

Values:

  • kInvalidValue = 0xFFFFFFFF -

    Invalid value or operand id.

  • kInvalidReg = 0xFF -

    Invalid register index.

  • kBufferGrow = 32U -

    Minimum reserved bytes in Buffer.

  • kMemAllocMinimum = 4096 -

    Minimum size of assembler/compiler code buffer.

  • kMemAllocGrowMax = 8192 * 1024 -

    Memory grow threshold.

    After the grow threshold is reached the capacity won’t be doubled anymore.

  • kMemAllocOverhead = sizeof(intptr_t) * 4 -

    Host memory allocator overhead.

    We decrement the overhead from our pools so the host operating system doesn’t need allocate an extra virtual page to put the data it needs to manage the requested memory block (for example if a single virtual page is 4096 and we require the same memory size we decrease our requirement by kMemAllocOverhead).

    Arm architecture.

kSeg enum

X86/X64 segment codes.

Values:

  • kSegDefault = 0 -

    No segment.

  • kSegEs = 1 -

    Es segment.

  • kSegCs = 2 -

    Cs segment.

  • kSegSs = 3 -

    Ss segment.

  • kSegDs = 4 -

    Ds segment.

  • kSegFs = 5 -

    Fs segment.

  • kSegGs = 6 -

    Gs segment.

kMemVSib enum

X86/X64 index register legacy and AVX2 (VSIB) support.

Values:

  • kMemVSibGpz = 0 -

    Memory operand uses Gp or no index register.

  • kMemVSibXmm = 1 -

    Memory operand uses Xmm or no index register.

  • kMemVSibYmm = 2 -

    Memory operand uses Ymm or no index register.

kMemFlags enum

Values:

  • kMemSegBits = 0x7 -
  • kMemSegIndex = 0 -
  • kMemSegMask = kMemSegBits << kMemSegIndex -
  • kMemGpdBits = 0x1 -
  • kMemGpdIndex = 3 -
  • kMemGpdMask = kMemGpdBits << kMemGpdIndex -
  • kMemVSibBits = 0x3 -
  • kMemVSibIndex = 4 -
  • kMemVSibMask = kMemVSibBits << kMemVSibIndex -
  • kMemShiftBits = 0x3 -
  • kMemShiftIndex = 6 -
  • kMemShiftMask = kMemShiftBits << kMemShiftIndex -

X86/X64 Prefetch hints.

Values:

  • kPrefetchNta = 0 -

    Prefetch using NT hint.

  • kPrefetchT0 = 1 -

    Prefetch to L0 cache.

  • kPrefetchT1 = 2 -

    Prefetch to L1 cache.

  • kPrefetchT2 = 3 -

    Prefetch to L2 cache.

kInstOptions enum

X86/X64 instruction emit options, mainly for internal purposes.

Values:

  • kInstOptionLock = 0x10 -

    Emit instruction with LOCK prefix.

    If this option is used and instruction doesn’t support LOCK prefix an invalid instruction error is generated.

  • kInstOptionRex = 0x40 -

    Force REX prefix to be emitted.

    This option should be used carefully, because there are unencodable combinations. If you want to access ah, bh, ch or dh registers the REX prefix can’t be emitted, otherwise illegal instruction error will be returned.

  • kInstOptionVex3 = 0x80 -

    Force three-byte VEX prefix to be emitted (instead of more compact two-byte VEX prefix).

    Ignored if the instruction is not AVX instruction or extension to the instruction set that is encoded by using VEX prefix.

kInstGroup enum

X86/X64 instruction groups.

This should be only used by assembler, because it’s asmjit::Assembler specific grouping. Each group represents one ‘case’ in the Assembler’s main emit method.

Values:

  • kInstGroupNone -

    Never used.

  • kInstGroupX86Op -
  • kInstGroupX86Rm -
  • kInstGroupX86Rm_B -
  • kInstGroupX86RmReg -
  • kInstGroupX86RegRm -

    Adc/Add/And/Cmp/Or/Sbb/Sub/Xor.

    Bswap.

  • kInstGroupX86BTest -

    Bt/Btc/Btr/Bts.

  • kInstGroupX86Call -

    Call.

    Enter.

    Imul.

    Inc/Dec.

  • kInstGroupX86Int -

    Int.

  • kInstGroupX86Jcc -

    Jcc.

  • kInstGroupX86Jmp -

    Jmp.

  • kInstGroupX86Lea -

    Lea.

  • kInstGroupX86Mov -

    Mov.

  • kInstGroupX86MovSxZx -

    Movsx/Movsxd/Movzx.

  • kInstGroupX86MovPtr -

    Mov having absolute memory operand (x86/x64).

  • kInstGroupX86Push -

    Push.

  • kInstGroupX86Pop -

    Pop.

  • kInstGroupX86Rep -

    Rep/Repe/Repne LodsX/MovsX/StosX/CmpsX/ScasX.

  • kInstGroupX86Rot -

    Rcl/Rcr/Rol/Ror/Sal/Sar/Shl/Shr.

kInstOpCode enum

Instruction OpCode encoding used by asmjit ‘InstInfo‘ table.

The schema was inspired by AVX/AVX2 features.

Values:

  • kInstOpCode_MM_Shift = 16 -
  • kInstOpCode_MM_Mask = 0x0FU << kInstOpCode_MM_Shift -
  • kInstOpCode_MM_00 = 0x00U << kInstOpCode_MM_Shift -
  • kInstOpCode_MM_0F = 0x01U << kInstOpCode_MM_Shift -
  • kInstOpCode_MM_0F38 = 0x02U << kInstOpCode_MM_Shift -
  • kInstOpCode_MM_0F3A = 0x03U << kInstOpCode_MM_Shift -
  • kInstOpCode_MM_0F01 = 0x0FU << kInstOpCode_MM_Shift -
  • kInstOpCode_PP_Shift = 21 -
  • kInstOpCode_PP_Mask = 0x07U << kInstOpCode_PP_Shift -
  • kInstOpCode_PP_00 = 0x00U << kInstOpCode_PP_Shift -
  • kInstOpCode_PP_66 = 0x01U << kInstOpCode_PP_Shift -
  • kInstOpCode_PP_F3 = 0x02U << kInstOpCode_PP_Shift -
  • kInstOpCode_PP_F2 = 0x03U << kInstOpCode_PP_Shift -
  • kInstOpCode_PP_9B = 0x07U << kInstOpCode_PP_Shift -
  • kInstOpCode_L_Shift = 24 -
  • kInstOpCode_L_Mask = 0x01U << kInstOpCode_L_Shift -
  • kInstOpCode_L_False = 0x00U << kInstOpCode_L_Shift -
  • kInstOpCode_L_True = 0x01U << kInstOpCode_L_Shift -
  • kInstOpCode_O_Shift = 29 -
  • kInstOpCode_O_Mask = 0x07U << kInstOpCode_O_Shift -

kInstFlags enum

X86/X64 instruction type flags.

Values:

  • kInstFlagNone = 0x0000 -

    No flags.

  • kInstFlagFlow = 0x0001 -

    Instruction is a control-flow instruction.

    Control flow instructions are jmp, jcc, call and ret.

  • kInstFlagTest = 0x0002 -

    Instruction is a compare/test like instruction.

  • kInstFlagMove = 0x0004 -

    Instruction is a move like instruction.

    Move instructions typically overwrite the first operand by the second operand. The first operand can be the exact copy of the second operand or it can be any kind of conversion. Mov instructions are typically ‘mov’, ‘movd’, ‘movq’, ‘movdq?’, ‘cmov??’ like instructions, but we also consider ‘lea’ (Load Effective Address), multimedia instructions like ‘cvtdq2pd’, shuffle instructions like ‘pshufb’ and SSE/SSE2 mathematic instructions like ‘rcp??’, ‘round??’ and ‘rsqrt??’.

  • kInstFlagXchg = 0x0008 -

    Instruction is an exchange like instruction.

    Exchange instruction typically overwrite first and second operand, we count ‘xchg’ and ‘xadd’ instructions right now.

  • kInstFlagFp = 0x0010 -

    Instruction accesses Fp register(s).

  • kInstFlagLock = 0x0020 -

    Instruction can be prefixed by using the LOCK prefix.

  • kInstFlagSpecial = 0x0040 -

    Instruction is special, this is for Compiler.

  • kInstFlagSpecialMem = 0x0080 -

    Instruction always performs memory access.

    This flag is always combined with kInstFlagSpecial and signalizes that there is an implicit address which is accessed (usually EDI/RDI or ESI/EDI).

  • kInstFlagMem2 = 0x0100 -

    Instruction memory operand can refer to 16-bit address (used by FPU).

  • kInstFlagMem4 = 0x0200 -

    Instruction memory operand can refer to 32-bit address (used by FPU).

  • kInstFlagMem8 = 0x0400 -

    Instruction memory operand can refer to 64-bit address (used by FPU).

  • kInstFlagMem10 = 0x0800 -

    Instruction memory operand can refer to 80-bit address (used by FPU).

  • kInstFlagMem2_4 = kInstFlagMem2   | kInstFlagMem4 -

    Combination of kInstFlagMem2 and kInstFlagMem4.

  • kInstFlagMem2_4_8 = kInstFlagMem2_4 | kInstFlagMem8 -

    Combination of kInstFlagMem2 and kInstFlagMem4 and kInstFlagMem8.

  • kInstFlagMem4_8 = kInstFlagMem4   | kInstFlagMem8 -

    Combination of kInstFlagMem4 and kInstFlagMem8.

  • kInstFlagMem4_8_10 = kInstFlagMem4_8 | kInstFlagMem10 -

    Combination of kInstFlagMem4 and kInstFlagMem8 and kInstFlagMem10.

  • kInstFlagW = 0x8000 -

    REX.W/VEX.W by default.

kInstOp enum

X86/X64 instruction operand flags.

Values:

  • kInstOpGb = 0x0001 -
  • kInstOpGw = 0x0002 -
  • kInstOpGd = 0x0004 -
  • kInstOpGq = 0x0008 -
  • kInstOpFp = 0x0010 -
  • kInstOpMm = 0x0020 -
  • kInstOpXmm = 0x0100 -

kVarType enum

X86/X64 variable type.

Values:

  • kVarTypeMm = 12 -

    Variable is Mm (MMX).

  • kVarTypeXmm -

    Variable is Xmm (SSE/SSE2).

  • kVarTypeXmmSs -

    Variable is SSE scalar SP-FP number.

  • kVarTypeXmmPs -

    Variable is SSE packed SP-FP number (4 floats).

  • kVarTypeXmmSd -

    Variable is SSE2 scalar DP-FP number.

  • kVarTypeXmmPd -

    Variable is SSE2 packed DP-FP number (2 doubles).

  • kVarTypeYmm -

    Variable is Ymm (AVX).

  • kVarTypeYmmPs -

    Variable is AVX packed SP-FP number (8 floats).

  • kVarTypeYmmPd -

    Variable is AVX packed DP-FP number (4 doubles).

  • kVarTypeCount -

    Count of variable types.

  • _kVarTypeMmStart = kVarTypeMm -
  • _kVarTypeMmEnd = kVarTypeMm -
  • _kVarTypeXmmStart = kVarTypeXmm -
  • _kVarTypeXmmEnd = kVarTypeXmmPd -
  • _kVarTypeYmmStart = kVarTypeYmm -
  • _kVarTypeYmmEnd = kVarTypeYmmPd -

kVarDesc enum

X86/X64 variable description.

Values:

  • kVarDescSp = 0x10 -

    Variable contains single-precision floating-point(s).

  • kVarDescDp = 0x20 -

    Variable contains double-precision floating-point(s).

  • kVarDescPacked = 0x40 -

    Variable is packed (for example float4x, double2x, ...).

kFuncConv enum

X86 function calling conventions.

Calling convention is scheme how function arguments are passed into function and how functions returns values. In assembler programming it’s needed to always comply with function calling conventions, because even small inconsistency can cause undefined behavior or crash.

List of calling conventions for 32-bit x86 mode:

List of calling conventions for 64-bit x86 mode (x64):

There is also kFuncConvHost that is defined to fit best to your compiler.

These types are used together with asmjit::Compiler::addFunc() method.

Values:

  • kFuncConvX64W = 1 -

    X64 calling convention for Windows platform (WIN64 ABI).

    For first four arguments are used these registers:

    Note first four arguments here means arguments at positions from 1 to 4 (included). For example if second argument is not passed in register then rdx/xmm1 register is unused.

    All other arguments are pushed on the stack in right-to-left direction. Stack is aligned by 16 bytes. There is 32-byte shadow space on the stack that can be used to save up to four 64-bit registers (probably designed to be used to save first four arguments passed in registers).

    Arguments direction:

    Stack is cleaned by:

    Return value:

    Stack is always aligned by 16 bytes.

    More information about this calling convention can be found on MSDN: .

  • kFuncConvX64U = 2 -

    X64 calling convention for Unix platforms (AMD64 ABI).

    First six 32 or 64-bit integer arguments are passed in rdi, rsi, rdx, rcx, r8, r9 registers. First eight floating point or Xmm arguments are passed in xmm0, xmm1, xmm2, xmm3, xmm4, xmm5, xmm6, xmm7 registers. This means that in registers can be transferred up to 14 arguments total.

    There is also RED ZONE below the stack pointer that can be used for temporary storage. The red zone is the space from [rsp-128] to [rsp-8].

    Arguments direction:

    Stack is cleaned by:

    Return value:

    Stack is always aligned by 16 bytes.

  • kFuncConvCDecl = 3 -

    Cdecl calling convention (used by C runtime).

    Compatible across MSVC and GCC.

    Arguments direction:

    Stack is cleaned by:

  • kFuncConvStdCall = 4 -

    Stdcall calling convention (used by WinAPI).

    Compatible across MSVC and GCC.

    Arguments direction:

    Stack is cleaned by:

    Return value:

  • kFuncConvMsThisCall = 5 -

    MSVC specific calling convention used by MSVC/Intel compilers for struct/class methods.

    This is MSVC (and Intel) only calling convention used in Windows world for C++ class methods. Implicit ‘this’ pointer is stored in ECX register instead of storing it on the stack.

    Arguments direction:

    Stack is cleaned by:

    Return value:

    C++ class methods that have variable count of arguments uses different calling convention called cdecl.

    Note

    This calling convention is always used by MSVC for class methods, it’s implicit and there is no way how to override it.

  • kFuncConvMsFastCall = 6 -

    MSVC specific fastcall.

    Two first parameters (evaluated from left-to-right) are in ECX:EDX registers, all others on the stack in right-to-left order.

    Arguments direction:

    Stack is cleaned by:

    Return value:

    Note

    This calling convention differs to GCC one in stack cleaning mechanism.

  • kFuncConvBorlandFastCall = 7 -

    Borland specific fastcall with 2 parameters in registers.

    Two first parameters (evaluated from left-to-right) are in ECX:EDX registers, all others on the stack in left-to-right order.

    Arguments direction:

    Stack is cleaned by:

    Return value:

    Note

    Arguments on the stack are in left-to-right order that differs to other fastcall conventions used in different compilers.

  • kFuncConvGccFastCall = 8 -

    GCC specific fastcall convention.

    Two first parameters (evaluated from left-to-right) are in ECX:EDX registers, all others on the stack in right-to-left order.

    Arguments direction:

    Stack is cleaned by:

    Return value:

    Note

    This calling convention should be compatible with kFuncConvMsFastCall.

  • kFuncConvGccRegParm1 = 9 -

    GCC specific regparm(1) convention.

    The first parameter (evaluated from left-to-right) is in EAX register, all others on the stack in right-to-left order.

    Arguments direction:

    Stack is cleaned by:

    Return value:

  • kFuncConvGccRegParm2 = 10 -

    GCC specific regparm(2) convention.

    Two first parameters (evaluated from left-to-right) are in EAX:EDX registers, all others on the stack in right-to-left order.

    Arguments direction:

    Stack is cleaned by:

    Return value:

  • kFuncConvGccRegParm3 = 11 -

    GCC specific fastcall with 3 parameters in registers.

    Three first parameters (evaluated from left-to-right) are in EAX:EDX:ECX registers, all others on the stack in right-to-left order.

    Arguments direction:

    Stack is cleaned by:

    Return value:

  • _kFuncConvCount = 12 -
  • kFuncConvHost = kFuncConvX64U -
  • kFuncConvHostCDecl = kFuncConvHost -
  • kFuncConvHostStdCall = kFuncConvHost -
  • kFuncConvHostFastCall = kFuncConvHost -
  • kFuncConvHost = kFuncConvX64U -
  • kFuncConvHostCDecl = kFuncConvHost -
  • kFuncConvHostStdCall = kFuncConvHost -
  • kFuncConvHostFastCall = kFuncConvHost -

kFuncHint enum

X86 function hints.

Values:

  • kFuncHintPushPop = 16 -

    Use push/pop sequences instead of mov sequences in function prolog and epilog.

  • kFuncHintEmms = 17 -

    Add emms instruction to the function epilog.

  • kFuncHintSFence = 18 -

    Add sfence instruction to the function epilog.

  • kFuncHintLFence = 19 -

    Add lfence instruction to the function epilog.

kFuncFlags enum

X86 function flags.

Values:

  • kFuncFlagPushPop = 0x00010000 -

    Whether to emit register load/save sequence using push/pop pairs.

  • kFuncFlagEnter = 0x00020000 -

    Whether to emit “enter” instead of three instructions in case that the function is not naked or misaligned.

  • kFuncFlagLeave = 0x00040000 -

    Whether to emit “leave” instead of two instructions in case that the function is not naked or misaligned.

  • kFuncFlagMoveArgs = 0x00080000 -

    Whether it’s required to move arguments to a new stack location, because of manual aligning.

  • kFuncFlagEmms = 0x01000000 -

    Whether to emit EMMS instruction in epilog (auto-detected).

  • kFuncFlagSFence = 0x02000000 -

    Whether to emit SFence instruction in epilog (auto-detected).

    Note

    kFuncFlagSFence and kFuncFlagLFence combination will result in emitting mfence.

  • kFuncFlagLFence = 0x04000000 -

    Whether to emit LFence instruction in epilog (auto-detected).

    Note

    kFuncFlagSFence and kFuncFlagLFence combination will result in emitting mfence.

uint8_t mm_shuffle(uint8_t z, uint8_t y, uint8_t x, uint8_t w)

Create Shuffle Constant for MMX/SSE shuffle instrutions.

Shuffle constants can be used to make immediate value for these intrinsics:

Parameters
  • z -

    First component position, number at interval [0, 3] inclusive.

  • x -

    Second component position, number at interval [0, 3] inclusive.

  • y -

    Third component position, number at interval [0, 3] inclusive.

  • w -

    Fourth component position, number at interval [0, 3] inclusive.

ASMJIT_ASSERT(_Exp_)

Assertion macro. Default implementation calls asmjit::assertionFailed() function.

Functions

template < typename T, typename Z >
T asmjit_cast(Z * p)

Cast used to cast pointer to function. It’s like reinterpret_cast<>, but uses internally C style cast to work with MinGW.

If you are using single compiler and reinterpret_cast<> works for you, there is no reason to use asmjit_cast<>. If you are writing cross-platform software with various compiler support, consider using asmjit_cast<> instead of reinterpret_cast<>.

kCpuFeature enum

Values:

  • kCpuFeatureMultithreading = 1 -

    Cpu has SSE3.

kRegType enum

X86/X64 register types.

Values:

  • kRegTypeGpbLo = 0x01 -

    Gpb-lo register (AL, BL, CL, DL, ...).

  • kRegTypeGpbHi = 0x02 -

    Gpb-hi register (AH, BH, CH, DH only).

  • kRegTypePatchedGpbHi = kRegTypeGpbLo | kRegTypeGpbHi -
  • kRegTypeGpw = 0x10 -

    Gpw register.

  • kRegTypeGpd = 0x20 -

    Gpd register.

  • kRegTypeGpq = 0x30 -

    Gpq register.

  • kRegTypeFp = 0x50 -

    Fp register.

  • kRegTypeMm = 0x60 -

    Mm register.

  • kRegTypeXmm = 0x70 -

    Xmm register.

  • kRegTypeYmm = 0x80 -

    Ymm register.

  • kRegTypeZmm = 0x90 -

    Zmm register.

  • kRegTypeSeg = 0xF0 -

    Segment register.

kRegIndex enum

kInstOptions enum

X86/X64 instruction emit options, mainly for internal purposes.

Values:

  • kInstOptionLock = 0x10 -

    Emit instruction with LOCK prefix.

    If this option is used and instruction doesn’t support LOCK prefix an invalid instruction error is generated.

  • kInstOptionRex = 0x40 -

    Force REX prefix to be emitted.

    This option should be used carefully, because there are unencodable combinations. If you want to access ah, bh, ch or dh registers the REX prefix can’t be emitted, otherwise illegal instruction error will be returned.

  • kInstOptionVex3 = 0x80 -

    Force three-byte VEX prefix to be emitted (instead of more compact two-byte VEX prefix).

    Ignored if the instruction is not AVX instruction or extension to the instruction set that is encoded by using VEX prefix.

kInstGroup enum

X86/X64 instruction groups.

This should be only used by assembler, because it’s asmjit::Assembler specific grouping. Each group represents one ‘case’ in the Assembler’s main emit method.

Values:

  • kInstGroupNone -

    Never used.

  • kInstGroupX86Op -
  • kInstGroupX86Rm -
  • kInstGroupX86Rm_B -
  • kInstGroupX86RmReg -
  • kInstGroupX86RegRm -
  • kInstGroupX86M -
  • kInstGroupX86Arith -

    Adc/Add/And/Cmp/Or/Sbb/Sub/Xor.

  • kInstGroupX86BSwap -

    Bswap.

  • kInstGroupX86BTest -

    Bt/Btc/Btr/Bts.

  • kInstGroupX86Call -

    Call.

  • kInstGroupX86Enter -

    Enter.

  • kInstGroupX86Imul -

    Imul.

  • kInstGroupX86IncDec -

kInstOpCode enum

Instruction OpCode encoding used by asmjit ‘InstInfo‘ table.

The schema was inspired by AVX/AVX2 features.

Values:

  • kInstOpCode_MM_Shift = 16 -
  • kInstOpCode_MM_Mask = 0x0FU << kInstOpCode_MM_Shift -
  • kInstOpCode_MM_00 = 0x00U << kInstOpCode_MM_Shift -
  • kInstOpCode_MM_0F = 0x01U << kInstOpCode_MM_Shift -
  • kInstOpCode_MM_0F38 = 0x02U << kInstOpCode_MM_Shift -
  • kInstOpCode_MM_0F3A = 0x03U << kInstOpCode_MM_Shift -
  • kInstOpCode_MM_0F01 = 0x0FU << kInstOpCode_MM_Shift -
  • kInstOpCode_PP_Shift = 21 -
  • kInstOpCode_PP_Mask = 0x07U << kInstOpCode_PP_Shift -
  • kInstOpCode_PP_00 = 0x00U << kInstOpCode_PP_Shift -
  • kInstOpCode_PP_66 = 0x01U << kInstOpCode_PP_Shift -
  • kInstOpCode_PP_F3 = 0x02U << kInstOpCode_PP_Shift -
  • kInstOpCode_PP_F2 = 0x03U << kInstOpCode_PP_Shift -
  • kInstOpCode_PP_9B = 0x07U << kInstOpCode_PP_Shift -
  • kInstOpCode_L_Shift = 24 -
  • kInstOpCode_L_Mask = 0x01U << kInstOpCode_L_Shift -
  • kInstOpCode_L_False = 0x00U << kInstOpCode_L_Shift -
  • kInstOpCode_L_True = 0x01U << kInstOpCode_L_Shift -
  • kInstOpCode_O_Shift = 29 -
  • kInstOpCode_O_Mask = 0x07U << kInstOpCode_O_Shift -

kInstFlags enum

X86/X64 instruction type flags.

Values:

  • kInstFlagNone = 0x0000 -

    No flags.

  • kInstFlagFlow = 0x0001 -

    Instruction is a control-flow instruction.

    Control flow instructions are jmp, jcc, call and ret.

  • kInstFlagTest = 0x0002 -

    Instruction is a compare/test like instruction.

  • kInstFlagMove = 0x0004 -

    Instruction is a move like instruction.

    Move instructions typically overwrite the first operand by the second operand. The first operand can be the exact copy of the second operand or it can be any kind of conversion. Mov instructions are typically ‘mov’, ‘movd’, ‘movq’, ‘movdq?’, ‘cmov??’ like instructions, but we also consider ‘lea’ (Load Effective Address), multimedia instructions like ‘cvtdq2pd’, shuffle instructions like ‘pshufb’ and SSE/SSE2 mathematic instructions like ‘rcp??’, ‘round??’ and ‘rsqrt??’.

  • kInstFlagXchg = 0x0008 -

    Instruction is an exchange like instruction.

    Exchange instruction typically overwrite first and second operand, we count ‘xchg’ and ‘xadd’ instructions right now.

  • kInstFlagFp = 0x0010 -

    Instruction accesses Fp register(s).

  • kInstFlagLock = 0x0020 -

    Instruction can be prefixed by using the LOCK prefix.

  • kInstFlagSpecial = 0x0040 -

    Instruction is special, this is for Compiler.

  • kInstFlagSpecialMem = 0x0080 -

    Instruction always performs memory access.

    This flag is always combined with kInstFlagSpecial and signalizes that there is an implicit address which is accessed (usually EDI/RDI or ESI/EDI).

  • kInstFlagMem2 = 0x0100 -

    Instruction memory operand can refer to 16-bit address (used by FPU).

  • kInstFlagMem4 = 0x0200 -

    Instruction memory operand can refer to 32-bit address (used by FPU).

  • kInstFlagMem8 = 0x0400 -

    Instruction memory operand can refer to 64-bit address (used by FPU).

  • kInstFlagMem10 = 0x0800 -

    Instruction memory operand can refer to 80-bit address (used by FPU).

  • kInstFlagMem2_4 = kInstFlagMem2   | kInstFlagMem4 -

    Combination of kInstFlagMem2 and kInstFlagMem4.

  • kInstFlagMem2_4_8 = kInstFlagMem2_4 | kInstFlagMem8 -

    Combination of kInstFlagMem2 and kInstFlagMem4 and kInstFlagMem8.

  • kInstFlagMem4_8 = kInstFlagMem4   | kInstFlagMem8 -

    Combination of kInstFlagMem4 and kInstFlagMem8.

  • kInstFlagMem4_8_10 = kInstFlagMem4_8 | kInstFlagMem10 -

    Combination of kInstFlagMem4 and kInstFlagMem8 and kInstFlagMem10.

  • kInstFlagW = 0x8000 -

    REX.W/VEX.W by default.

kFuncConv enum

X86 function calling conventions.

Calling convention is scheme how function arguments are passed into function and how functions returns values. In assembler programming it’s needed to always comply with function calling conventions, because even small inconsistency can cause undefined behavior or crash.

List of calling conventions for 32-bit x86 mode:

List of calling conventions for 64-bit x86 mode (x64):

There is also kFuncConvHost that is defined to fit best to your compiler.

These types are used together with asmjit::Compiler::addFunc() method.

Values:

  • kFuncConvX64W = 1 -

    X64 calling convention for Windows platform (WIN64 ABI).

    For first four arguments are used these registers:

    Note first four arguments here means arguments at positions from 1 to 4 (included). For example if second argument is not passed in register then rdx/xmm1 register is unused.

    All other arguments are pushed on the stack in right-to-left direction. Stack is aligned by 16 bytes. There is 32-byte shadow space on the stack that can be used to save up to four 64-bit registers (probably designed to be used to save first four arguments passed in registers).

    Arguments direction:

    Stack is cleaned by:

    Return value:

    Stack is always aligned by 16 bytes.

    More information about this calling convention can be found on MSDN: .

  • kFuncConvX64U = 2 -

    X64 calling convention for Unix platforms (AMD64 ABI).

    First six 32 or 64-bit integer arguments are passed in rdi, rsi, rdx, rcx, r8, r9 registers. First eight floating point or Xmm arguments are passed in xmm0, xmm1, xmm2, xmm3, xmm4, xmm5, xmm6, xmm7 registers. This means that in registers can be transferred up to 14 arguments total.

    There is also RED ZONE below the stack pointer that can be used for temporary storage. The red zone is the space from [rsp-128] to [rsp-8].

    Arguments direction:

    Stack is cleaned by:

    Return value:

    Stack is always aligned by 16 bytes.

  • kFuncConvCDecl = 3 -

    Cdecl calling convention (used by C runtime).

    Compatible across MSVC and GCC.

    Arguments direction:

    Stack is cleaned by:

  • kFuncConvStdCall = 4 -

    Stdcall calling convention (used by WinAPI).

    Compatible across MSVC and GCC.

    Arguments direction:

    Stack is cleaned by:

    Return value:

  • kFuncConvMsThisCall = 5 -

    MSVC specific calling convention used by MSVC/Intel compilers for struct/class methods.

    This is MSVC (and Intel) only calling convention used in Windows world for C++ class methods. Implicit ‘this’ pointer is stored in ECX register instead of storing it on the stack.

    Arguments direction:

    Stack is cleaned by:

    Return value:

    C++ class methods that have variable count of arguments uses different calling convention called cdecl.

    Note

    This calling convention is always used by MSVC for class methods, it’s implicit and there is no way how to override it.

  • kFuncConvMsFastCall = 6 -

    MSVC specific fastcall.

    Two first parameters (evaluated from left-to-right) are in ECX:EDX registers, all others on the stack in right-to-left order.

    Arguments direction:

    Stack is cleaned by:

    Return value:

    Note

    This calling convention differs to GCC one in stack cleaning mechanism.

  • kFuncConvBorlandFastCall = 7 -

    Borland specific fastcall with 2 parameters in registers.

    Two first parameters (evaluated from left-to-right) are in ECX:EDX registers, all others on the stack in left-to-right order.

    Arguments direction:

    Stack is cleaned by:

    Return value:

    Note

    Arguments on the stack are in left-to-right order that differs to other fastcall conventions used in different compilers.

  • kFuncConvGccFastCall = 8 -

    GCC specific fastcall convention.

    Two first parameters (evaluated from left-to-right) are in ECX:EDX registers, all others on the stack in right-to-left order.

    Arguments direction:

    Stack is cleaned by:

    Return value:

    Note

    This calling convention should be compatible with kFuncConvMsFastCall.

  • kFuncConvGccRegParm1 = 9 -

    GCC specific regparm(1) convention.

    The first parameter (evaluated from left-to-right) is in EAX register, all others on the stack in right-to-left order.

    Arguments direction:

    Stack is cleaned by:

    Return value:

  • kFuncConvGccRegParm2 = 10 -

    GCC specific regparm(2) convention.

    Two first parameters (evaluated from left-to-right) are in EAX:EDX registers, all others on the stack in right-to-left order.

    Arguments direction:

    Stack is cleaned by:

    Return value:

  • kFuncConvGccRegParm3 = 11 -

    GCC specific fastcall with 3 parameters in registers.

    Three first parameters (evaluated from left-to-right) are in EAX:EDX:ECX registers, all others on the stack in right-to-left order.

    Arguments direction:

    Stack is cleaned by:

    Return value:

  • _kFuncConvCount = 12 -
  • kFuncConvHost = kFuncConvX64U -
  • kFuncConvHostCDecl = kFuncConvHost -
  • kFuncConvHostStdCall = kFuncConvHost -
  • kFuncConvHostFastCall = kFuncConvHost -
  • kFuncConvHost = kFuncConvX64U -
  • kFuncConvHostCDecl = kFuncConvHost -
  • kFuncConvHostStdCall = kFuncConvHost -
  • kFuncConvHostFastCall = kFuncConvHost -

kFuncHint enum

X86 function hints.

Values:

  • kFuncHintPushPop = 16 -

    Use push/pop sequences instead of mov sequences in function prolog and epilog.

  • kFuncHintEmms = 17 -

    Add emms instruction to the function epilog.

  • kFuncHintSFence = 18 -

    Add sfence instruction to the function epilog.

  • kFuncHintLFence = 19 -

    Add lfence instruction to the function epilog.

kFuncFlags enum

X86 function flags.

Values:

  • kFuncFlagPushPop = 0x00010000 -

    Whether to emit register load/save sequence using push/pop pairs.

  • kFuncFlagEnter = 0x00020000 -

    Whether to emit “enter” instead of three instructions in case that the function is not naked or misaligned.

  • kFuncFlagLeave = 0x00040000 -

    Whether to emit “leave” instead of two instructions in case that the function is not naked or misaligned.

  • kFuncFlagMoveArgs = 0x00080000 -

    Whether it’s required to move arguments to a new stack location, because of manual aligning.

  • kFuncFlagEmms = 0x01000000 -

    Whether to emit EMMS instruction in epilog (auto-detected).

  • kFuncFlagSFence = 0x02000000 -

    Whether to emit SFence instruction in epilog (auto-detected).

    Note

    kFuncFlagSFence and kFuncFlagLFence combination will result in emitting mfence.

  • kFuncFlagLFence = 0x04000000 -

    Whether to emit LFence instruction in epilog (auto-detected).

    Note

    kFuncFlagSFence and kFuncFlagLFence combination will result in emitting mfence.

group asmjit_cpuinfo

X86 or x64 cpuid instruction allows to get information about processor vendor and it’s features. It’s always used to detect features like MMX, SSE and other newer ones.

AsmJit library supports low level cpuid call implemented internally as C++ function using inline assembler or intrinsics and also higher level CPU features detection. The low level function (also used by higher level one) is asmjit::cpuid().

AsmJit library also contains higher level function asmjit::getCpu() that returns features detected by the library. The detection process is done only once and the returned object is always the same. asmjit::BaseCpu structure not contains only information through asmjit::cpuid(), but there is also small multiplatform code to detect number of processors (or cores) through operating system API.

It’s recommended to use asmjit::cpuInfo to detect and check for host processor features.

Example how to use asmjit::cpuid():

 // All functions and structures are in asmjit namesapce.
 using namespace asmjit;

 // Here will be retrieved result of cpuid call.
 CpuId out;

 // Use cpuid function to do the job.
 cpuid(0 /* eax */, &out /* eax, ebx, ecx, edx */);

 // If eax argument to cpuid is 0, ebx, ecx and edx registers
 // are filled with cpu vendor.
 char vendor[13];
 memcpy(i->vendor, &out.ebx, 4);
 memcpy(i->vendor + 4, &out.edx, 4);
 memcpy(i->vendor + 8, &out.ecx, 4);
 vendor[12] = '\0';

 // Print vendor
 puts(vendor);

If the high-level interface of asmjit::BaseCpu is not enough, you can use low-level asmjit::cpuid() when running on x86/x64 host, but please read processor manuals provided by Intel, AMD or other manufacturer for cpuid details.

Example of using asmjit::BaseCpu::getHost():

 // All functions and structures are in asmjit namesapce.
 using namespace asmjit;

 // Call to cpuInfo return BaseCpu structure that shouldn't be modified.
 // Make it const by default.
 const BaseCpu* cpu = BaseCpu::getHost();

 // Now you are able to get specific features.

 // Processor has SSE2
 if (cpu->features & kCpuFeatureSse2) {
   // your code...
 }
 // Processor has MMX
 else if (cpu->features & kCpuFeature_MMX) {
   // your code...
 }
 // Processor is old, no SSE2 or MMX support.
 else {
   // your code...
 }

Better example is in app/test/testcpu.cpp file.

Contains macros that can be redefined to fit into any project.

group asmjit_logging

Contains classes related to loging. Currently logging is implemented in asmjit::BaseLogger class. The function asmjit::BaseLogger::log() can be overridden to redirect logging into any user-defined stream.

To log your assembler output to FILE stream use this code:

 // Create assembler
 Assembler a;

 // Create and set file based logger
 FileLogger logger(stderr);
 a.setLogger(&logger);

You can see that logging goes through Assembler. If you are using Compiler and you want to log messages in correct assembler order, you should look at Compiler::comment() method. It allows you to insert text message into items stream so the Compiler is able to send messages to Assembler in correct order.

See
asmjit::BaseLogger, asmjit::FileLogger.

Enums

kCodeGen enum

CodeGen features.

Values:

  • kCodeGenOptimizedAlign = 0 -

    Emit optimized code-alignment sequences.

    X86/X64:

    Default align sequence used by X86/X64 architecture is one-byte 0x90 opcode that is mostly shown by disassemblers as nop. However there are more optimized align sequences for 2-11 bytes that may execute faster. If this feature is enabled asmjit will generate specialized sequences for alignment between 1 to 11 bytes. Also when x86x64::Compiler is used, it may add rex prefixes into the code to make some instructions larger so no alignment sequences are needed.

    true.

  • kCodeGenPredictedJumps = 1 -

    Emit jump-prediction hints.

    X86/X64:

    Jump prediction is usually based on the direction of the jump. If the jump is backward it is usually predicted as taken; and if the jump is forward it is usually predicted as not-taken. The reason is that loops generally use backward jumps and conditions usually use forward jumps. However this behavior can be overridden by using instruction prefixes. If this option is enabled these hints will be emitted.

    true.

kCpuVendor enum

Cpu vendor IDs.

Cpu vendor IDs are specific for AsmJit library. Vendor ID is not directly read from cpuid result, instead it’s based on CPU vendor string.

Values:

  • kCpuVendorUnknown = 0 -

    Unknown CPU vendor.

  • kCpuVendorIntel = 1 -

    Intel CPU vendor.

  • kCpuVendorAmd = 2 -

    AMD CPU vendor.

  • kCpuVendorNSM = 3 -

    National Semiconductor CPU vendor (applies also to Cyrix processors).

  • kCpuVendorTransmeta = 4 -

    Transmeta CPU vendor.

  • kCpuVendorVia = 5 -

    VIA CPU vendor.

kInstCode enum

Instruction codes (stub).

Values:

  • kInstNone = 0 -

    No instruction.

kInstOptions enum

Instruction options (stub).

Values:

  • kInstOptionNone = 0x00 -

    No instruction options.

  • kInstOptionShortForm = 0x01 -

    Emit short form of the instruction.

    X86/X64:

    Short form is mostly related to jmp and jcc instructions, but can be used by other instructions supporting 8-bit or 32-bit immediates. This option can be dangerous if the short jmp/jcc is required, but not encodable due to large displacement, in such case an error happens and the whole assembler/compiler stream is unusable.

  • kInstOptionLongForm = 0x02 -

    Emit long form of the instruction.

    X86/X64:

    Long form is mosrlt related to jmp and jcc instructions, but like the kInstOptionShortForm option it can be used by other instructions supporting both 8-bit and 32-bit immediates.

  • kInstOptionTaken = 0x04 -

    Condition is likely to be taken (instruction).

  • kInstOptionNotTaken = 0x08 -

    Condition is unlikely to be taken (instruction).

kMemType enum

Type of memory operand.

Values:

  • kMemTypeBaseIndex = 0 -

    Memory operand is a combination of base register, optional index register and optional displacement.

    Note

    The Assembler interprets kMemTypeBaseIndex and kMemTypeStackIndex types the same way, but Compiler interprets kMemTypeBaseIndex as [base + index] and kMemTypeStackIndex as [stack(base) + index].

  • kMemTypeStackIndex = 1 -

    Memory operand is a combination of variable’s memory location, optional index register and displacement.

    Note

    The Assembler interprets kMemTypeBaseIndex and kMemTypeStackIndex types in the same way, but Compiler interprets kMemTypeBaseIndex as [base + index] and kMemTypeStackIndex as [stack(base) + index].

  • kMemTypeLabel = 2 -

    Memory operand refers to the memory location specified by a label.

  • kMemTypeAbsolute = 3 -

    Memory operand is an absolute memory location.

    Supported mostly by x86, truncated to a 32-bit value when running in 64-bit mode (x64).
